          "text": "The user has two questions:\n\n1. For пустой ввод (empty input) - code 66, and for EOF - what code? Let me re-read the requirements.\n\nFrom §6.1 Task 2: \"Пустое имя и EOF — два разных случая с разной диагностикой.\"\n\nAnd from §4.9 п.6: exit codes: 64 — usage, 65 — data, 66 — no input, 74 — IO failure.\n\nSo the mapping should be:\n- EOF (no input at all, e.g. `type nul |`) → `exit_code::no_in` (66) — нет входных данных\n- Пустое имя (строка считана, но пустая) → `exit_code::data` (65) — данные некорректны\n- Пустое имя после trim → тоже `exit_code::data` (65)\n\nWait, in my earlier plan I had it the other way: EOF → 66, empty → 65. But she's asking \"для пустого ввода код ошибки 66 а для EOF тогда?\" — she seems to think empty input should be 66 and EOF... what?\n\nLet me re-read her question. She's saying: for пустой ввод (empty input) the error code is 66, and for EOF then what?\n\nActually I think she's confused because in Task 1, `type nul` returned 66 (no input). So she's associating \"пустой ввод\" with 66. But in Task 2 we need to differentiate:\n\n- `type nul | prog` → EOF → no input at all → 66\n- `echo; | prog` → empty line read → пустое имя → 65\n\nBut she's asking \"для пустого ввода код ошибки 66 а для EOF тогда?\" — maybe she's thinking about the Task 1 experience where `type nul` gave 66, and now we're saying empty name is also... hmm.\n\nLet me just clarify: пустой ввод (EOF, type nul) → 66. Пустое имя (echo;) → 65.\n\nWait, looking at it again from her perspective: In Task 1, `type nul | main.exe` returned 66 (no_in). In Task 2, she's thinking empty input = 66. But then what about EOF?\n\nActually EOF **is** empty input (type nul). Let me re-read her question more carefully:\n\n\"для пустого ввода код ошибки 66 а для EOF тогда?\"\n\nI think she's saying: \"For empty input, error code 66, and for EOF then?\" — she might think they're different things. But EOF is what causes empty input detection when type nul is used.\n\nLet me